First, simplify the expression inside the square root. The numerator is \( \log(n^2) - (\log n)^2 \), which simplifies to \( 2 \log n - (\log n)^2 \). The denominator is \( \log n - 3 \). Thus, the expression becomes: \[ \frac{2 \log n - (\log n)^2}{\log n - 3} \] Let \( x = \log n \). The inequality becomes: \[ \frac{x(2 - x)}{x - 3} \geq 0 \] The critical points are \( x = 0 \), \( x = 2 \), and \( x = 3 \). We analyze the sign of the expression in the intervals determined by these points: 1. \( (-\infty, 0) \): Positive 2. \( (0, 2) \): Negative 3. \( (2, 3) \): Positive 4. \( (3, \infty) \): Negative The expression is non-negative in \( (-\infty, 0] \) and \( (2, 3) \). Translating back to \( n \): 1. \( x \leq 0 \): \( \log n \leq 0 \implies 0 < n \leq 1 \). The only integer is \( n = 1 \). 2. \( 2 < x < 3 \): \( \log n > 2 \implies n > 100 \) and \( \log n < 3 \implies n < 1000 \). The integers are from 101 to 999 inclusive. Counting the integers: - \( n = 1 \): 1 integer - Integers from 101 to 999 inclusive: \( 999 - 101 + 1 = 899 \) Total integers: \( 1 + 899 = 900 \).
